    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but if the \"bedrock\" is law that actively forces people to violate their most deeply held moral or spiritual truths, isn't the state actually becoming coercive? it seems like you're framing the secular state as inherently neutral and \"fair,\" while framing religious conscience as a potential threat to equality. isn't it also possible that a truly \"healthy\" democracy is one that protects the individual's right to follow their conscience against the majority, even if it means the law isn't perfectly uniform?",
